      Russian bond payments
   =20
 =20
The rough theoretical situation is that the government of Russia owns a lot=
 of US dollars, it owes some of those US dollars to foreign bondholders, it=
 would like to pay the bondholders their dollars, and the bondholders would=
 like to receive them. But the US government has declared that US banks can=
=E2=80=99t move money on behalf of the Russian government; there was an exc=
eption for payments on Russia=E2=80=99s bonds, but that exception has ended=
. Russia=E2=80=99s bonds involve big US banks as paying agents, and if thos=
e banks won=E2=80=99t move the money then the money won=E2=80=99t move. And=
 then Russia will be in default on its bonds, an outcome that it would pref=
er to avoid.It =E2=80=A6=C2=A0feels =E2=80=A6=C2=A0like there could be a wo=
rkaround? Like in some loose sense, one wants to say =E2=80=9CRussia should=
 simply send dollars to its bondholders without involving those US banks.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But that is a conceptual error. A dollar=C2=A0is=C2=A0an ent=
ry on the books of a US bank. If you own dollars, what you own is a number =
in an account at a US bank.[1] Moving dollars means telling US=C2=A0banks t=
o reduce the number in your account and increase the number in someone else=
=E2=80=99s account. If you cut the US banks out of the process, there=E2=80=
=99s no process.Still there are some imperfect workarounds. One is: I say t=
hat a dollar=C2=A0is=C2=A0an entry on the books of a US bank, and that is m=
ostly true, but=C2=A0some=C2=A0dollars are green pieces of paper, actual ph=
ysical currency. If Russia has enough of those =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I have no=
 idea if it does =E2=80=94=C2=A0then I guess it could put them in sacks and=
 say to the bondholders =E2=80=9Chey if you want your interest payments com=
e to Moscow and take a sack.=E2=80=9D This is a very imperfect way to do in=
ternational finance, and I assume a lot of international bondholders would =
not want to come collect their sacks.Here=E2=80=99s another workaround. Rou=
ghly speaking, Russia still=C2=A0has its frozen US dollars. It can=E2=80=99=
t make its US banks transfer them, but I suppose it could issue transferabl=
e claims on them. For instance, if Russia=E2=80=99s government holds $1 bil=
lion in an account at a Russian bank, and that Russian bank in turn holds t=
hat $1 billion in a US correspondent bank, then in some sense the $1 billio=
n in the correspondent bank=E2=80=99s accounts are =E2=80=9Creal dollars=E2=
=80=9D and the $1 billion in the Russian bank=E2=80=99s accounts are =E2=80=
=9Cindirect claims on dollars.=E2=80=9D If Russia=E2=80=99s government call=
ed up the correspondent bank to say =E2=80=9Chey send that $1 billion to ou=
r bondholders,=E2=80=9D the correspondent bank, being US-regulated, would s=
ay no.But if it called up the Russian bank and said =E2=80=9Chey send that =
$1 billion to our bondholders,=E2=80=9D the Russian bank, being Russia-regu=
lated, would say yes. It couldn=E2=80=99t use the US banking system to do t=
hat, but it could=C2=A0open accounts for the bondholders=C2=A0at the Russia=
n bank, and move dollars into their accounts, and then the bondholders woul=
d =E2=80=9Chave=E2=80=9D the dollars. They would have numbers in their acco=
unts at the Russian bank, and those numbers would have dollar signs in fron=
t of them, and those numbers would represent claims on dollars in US bank a=
ccounts even if they are not exactly interchangeable with those dollars.And=
 then the bondholders=C2=A0could try to withdraw the dollars, I guess, by t=
elling the Russian bank to transfer the money to their accounts at their US=
 banks. That is where the system breaks down a bit: If you are the US bank,=
 and you know that this transfer comes from the Russian bond payment, do yo=
u reject it as a possible sanctions violation? I am not sure this actually =
gets usable dollars into the hands of the bondholders.=C2=A0Still, Russia i=
s going to=C2=A0try that one:Russia is planning a bond-payment mechanism to=
 sidestep US sanctions and a potential default as a grace period ticks down=
 on its latest missed coupons.The proposal would allow foreign investors to=
 open accounts in Russian banks in both rubles and hard currency, Finance M=
inister Anton Siluanov said in an interview with the Vedomosti newspaper. U=
nlike the previous payment system, investors will be able to access the fun=
ds without restriction, he was cited as saying. =C2=A0Russia is back in def=
ault countdown as coupon payments in euros and dollars worth about $100 mil=
lion had yet to trickle through to foreign investors=E2=80=99 accounts as o=
f Friday evening, effectively triggering a 30-day grace period.=C2=A0The tr=
ansfers were complicated last week when the US Treasury allowed a sanctions=
 loophole to expire, barring US banks and individuals from accepting bond p=
ayments from Russia=E2=80=99s government.The next slate of payments -- wort=
h about $400 million and due in June -- will take place =E2=80=9Coutside We=
stern financial infrastructure,=E2=80=9D Siluanov said in an interview show=
n Monday by Chinese state-run broadcaster CGTN. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CThis is h=
ow it works for gas payments: we get foreign currency, then it is converted=
 to rubles=E2=80=9D on behalf of the gas buyer, Vedomosti cited him as sayi=
ng. =E2=80=9CThe Eurobond settlement mechanism will operate in the same way=
, but in the opposite direction.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CI doubt it will=
 work -- for most foreign investors, the procedure for opening an account w=
ith a Russian bank may be too difficult,=E2=80=9D said Alexey Tretyakov, a =
portfolio manager at Aricapital in Moscow.=C2=A0=E2=80=9COnly the largest i=
nstitutional investors can cope. But they may face reputation risks and ris=
ks of sanctions violations when dealing with Russian counterparts.=E2=80=9D=
Yeah I mean having some US dollars in your bank account at a Russian bank i=
s=C2=A0something, though it is not quite as good as having US dollars in yo=
ur bank account at a US bank.
