      Greenwashing
   =20
 =20
A lot of financial misconduct has the following two elements:=09Doing some =
ambiguous thing, and=09Sending bad emails about it.I sometimes describe mar=
ket manipulation that way. Just buying a lot of stock will make the stock g=
o up, but buying a lot=C2=A0stock is not a crime. Buying a lot of stock and=
 saying =E2=80=9Clol I am pounding this stock to make it go up=E2=80=9D: cr=
ime.Environmental, social and governance investing is a big business, but i=
t is a relatively=C2=A0new=C2=A0big business, and we are in the early stage=
s of ESG enforcement, of=C2=A0regulators and prosecutors going after financ=
ial institutions for misrepresenting their ESG investment processes. But I =
suspect it is going to end up looking a lot like market manipulation: =E2=
=80=9CGreenwashing=E2=80=9D will mean (1) making ambiguously ESG investment=
 choices (buying fossil-fuel companies, etc.) in ESG funds and (2) sending =
emails saying things like =E2=80=9Cthis company is bad for ESG but we are b=
uying it anyway.=E2=80=9D ESG is a subjective and complex enough concept th=
at you can make the case that pretty much any investment=C2=A0is=C2=A0ESG, =
or=C2=A0is not=C2=A0ESG; what makes something =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing=E2=80=
=9D is evidence of=C2=A0intent.So we talked last week about the US Securiti=
es and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s first =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing=E2=80=9D e=
nforcement action, fining BNY Mellon Investment Adviser Inc. $1.5 million f=
or saying that some of its funds considered=C2=A0ESG factors for all of the=
ir investments, even though in fact they only considered ESG factors for 75=
% of those investments. A small fine, because the evidence of intent is not=
 snickering chats but simply an absence of ESG reports for some companies. =
I outlined what I think a bigger greenwashing case would look like:An ESG f=
und makes its ESG choices for non-ESG reasons, and has lots of emails and c=
hat transcripts to that effect. Somewhere on the fund=E2=80=99s servers the=
re is an email from a portfolio manager to its environmental analyst saying=
, like, =E2=80=9CThis company is a hideous polluter and would never meet th=
e ESG standards that we publish and that we use to attract investors, but t=
he stock keeps going up, can we ignore our standards so I can buy it,=E2=80=
=9D and the analyst replies =E2=80=9Csure, our bonuses are more important t=
han ESG, I=E2=80=99ll just write a fake report saying it=E2=80=99s good,=E2=
=80=9D and the portfolio manager replies =E2=80=9Cgreat, hope our investors=
 don=E2=80=99t find out about this ESG fraud we=E2=80=99re doing,=E2=80=9D =
and the analyst replies =E2=80=9Clolololol or the SEC, see you in jail!=E2=
=80=9D And then the SEC finds that email and prints it in a complaint and t=
he fund settles for $100 million.Meanwhile in Germany:Deutsche Bank AG and =
its asset management unit had their Frankfurt offices raided by police, add=
ing to the legal headaches facing Germany=E2=80=99s largest lender.Law enfo=
rcement officials on Tuesday morning entered the twin towers where Germany=
=E2=80=99s largest lender is headquartered, as well as the nearby premises =
of DWS Group, according to a statement from the prosecutor that confirmed a=
n earlier Bloomberg report. The search is related to accusations of greenwa=
shing against the asset manager. =E2=80=A6DWS has faced regulatory probes i=
n the US and Germany after its former chief sustainability officer, Desiree=
 Fixler, went public with greenwashing allegations last year. While the com=
pany has denied the claims, the raid adds to a list of regulatory and legal=
 issues for Deutsche Bank Chief Executive Officer Christian Sewing just as =
he emerges from a successful turnaround of the lender. =E2=80=A6Among other=
 things, Fixler has said that DWS=E2=80=99s claims that hundreds of billion=
s of its assets under management were =E2=80=9CESG integrated=E2=80=9D were=
 misleading because the label didn=E2=80=99t translate into meaningful acti=
on by relevant fund managers. DWS has since stopped using the label.See, yo=
u simply cannot storm into a bank and look for evidence that the =E2=80=9CE=
SG integrated=E2=80=9D label =E2=80=9Cdidn=E2=80=99t translate into meaning=
ful action by relevant fund managers.=E2=80=9D That label means that the fu=
nd managers thought about ESG stuff, and they thought about other stuff (wi=
ll the stocks go up), and then they made some decision about which stocks t=
o buy based on some weighting=C2=A0of those factors. Buying some coal stock=
, or whatever, is not proof that the ESG-integrated fund was somehow a frau=
d; perhaps the managers thought really hard about it and bought the stock a=
nyway.What=C2=A0is=C2=A0arguably proof of fraud, and what you=C2=A0can=C2=
=A0find in a raid, is an email from one fund manager to another saying =E2=
=80=9Cthis ESG stuff is so fake, I am not really going to consider it in ma=
king investment decisions.=E2=80=9D Or you could find an email from a susta=
inability analyst to the manager of an ESG-integrated fund saying =E2=80=9C=
this company is the worst polluter in Europe, you should not buy its stock =
for your fund,=E2=80=9D and the manager replying =E2=80=9Cbuzz off, sustain=
ability nerd, I=E2=80=99ll buy whatever I want, ESG is fake.=E2=80=9DBy the=
 way, there is a danger here. The more passionate ESG analysts you hire, th=
e more likely they are to send passionate emails saying =E2=80=9Cwe can=E2=
=80=99t buy this stock, it=E2=80=99s a terrible polluter.=E2=80=9D Sometime=
s they will be right and you won=E2=80=99t buy the stock. Other times, the =
ESG-integrated fund managers will consider their input carefully and then s=
ay =E2=80=9CI see your point, but I think you are overstating the problem, =
and anyway our mandate is to consider other factors, so I am going to buy s=
ome of the stock despite your objections.=E2=80=9D And then the passionate =
analyst will reply =E2=80=9Cyou monster, you are destroying the planet.=E2=
=80=9D And then the regulators will find those emails and you will get in t=
rouble for greenwashing.There are about three ways to avoid this:=09Do ever=
ything that your most passionate ESG analysts advocate, to avoid getting in=
 trouble for contradicting them.=09Have a rigorous culture of not putting a=
nything in writing, to avoid creating any embarrassing records.=09Don=E2=80=
=99t hire particularly passionate ESG analysts.The more that your culture e=
ncourages passionate analysts to advocate for tough ESG policies,=C2=A0the =
more awkward emails you will generate.[2] If you treat ESG as a box-ticking=
 exercise, the raids will find nothing. If you have robust internal debates=
 about ESG, some of those debates will leak out, the raids will find the mo=
st passionate objections that were overruled and they will look pretty bad.=
 And because greenwashing is doing bad ESG stuff and sending emails about i=
t, you will get in trouble.
