      An insider trading hypothetical
   =20
 =20
If you are the co-founder of a public company, and you leave the company bu=
t keep tens of millions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of stock, and then you co=
mmit a murder, and then, between the time that you commit the murder and th=
e time you are arrested for the murder, you sell some stock, and then you g=
et arrested and the stock drops because people are like =E2=80=9Chuh, murde=
rer co-founder=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=C2=A0have you committed insider trading? =
Obviously the murder is the bigger problem here, but this is a financial ne=
wsletter and we like insider trading hypotheticals. You sold stock before t=
he news came out, the news made the stock drop, you knew about the news in =
advance: Seems kind of like insider trading, huh?Or: If you=C2=A0didn=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0commit the murder, but know that you are a suspect, and you dump =
some stock before you get arrested and then the stock drops, is that also i=
nsider trading? If the police arrest you for the murder but can=E2=80=99t p=
rove you did it, but you sold stock, can they get you for insider trading?I=
 don=E2=80=99t know? Seems like a stretch.(Did you have some fiduciary=C2=
=A0obligation to the company or its shareholders not to trade on your murde=
ring news?) But I have argued that (1) everything is securities fraud =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0every bad thing that a public company does can be characterized=
 as securities fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0and (2) if that is true then, any time=
=C2=A0public-company executives sell=C2=A0stock while knowing about a bad t=
hing, that might be insider trading. So a chief executive officer who commi=
ts sexual harassment might also be guilty of insider trading, as long as he=
 sells some stock between the time he does the harassment and the time it b=
ecomes public. On that reasoning, sure, murder could also be insider tradin=
g.Last week I briefly linked to this story titled =E2=80=9CBiotech Founder =
Arrested in Murder-for-Hire Scheme,=E2=80=9D but a reader emailed to point =
out that it is also=C2=A0an insider trading story:The co-founder of Enochia=
n BioSciences Inc. was arrested this week after being indicted on charges h=
e was involved in a murder-for-hire scheme that led to the death of a Vermo=
nt man in 2018. =E2=80=A6Enochian shares fell nearly 37% to $3.70 on Wednes=
day.Enochian said in a statement that the incident leading to the arrest pr=
edates a merger that created Enochian in its current form and is completely=
 unrelated to the company.Chief Executive Mark Dybul said Dr. Gumrukcu has =
had no formal role in the company, and that his informal role as a scientif=
ic adviser has ended. =E2=80=A6Dr. Gumrukcu owns nearly a third of Enochian=
=E2=80=99s outstanding shares, and is the company=E2=80=99s largest shareho=
lder, according to data from FactSet.Last week, Dr. Gumrukcu sold about 253=
,000 shares at a price of $8 each, grossing over $2 million, according to s=
ecurities filings.Dr. Gumrukcu=E2=80=99s remaining holdings include 24.7 mi=
llion shares he owns directly and about 4.7 million shares owned by his spo=
use, according to the securities filings.Ehh, it=E2=80=99s just 1% of his s=
tock, which does not scream =E2=80=9Cdump stock before the murder charges.=
=E2=80=9D If he had sold all of his stock then you=E2=80=99d have something=
.=C2=A0
