<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Russian bond payments</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rough theoretical situation is tha=
t the government of Russia owns a lot of US dollars, it owes some of those =
US dollars to foreign bondholders, it would like to pay the bondholders the=
ir dollars, and the bondholders would like to receive them. But the US gove=
rnment has declared that US banks can=E2=80=99t move money on behalf of the=
 Russian government; there was an exception for payments on Russia=E2=80=99=
s bonds, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27899=
761.281614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90cmVhc3VyeS10by1ibG9jay11=
LXMtaW52ZXN0b3JzLWZyb20tcmVjZWl2aW5nLXJ1c3NpYW4tZGVidC1wYXltZW50cy0xMTY1MzQ=
yMDUzMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5d241e54" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">that exception has ended=
</a>. Russia=E2=80=99s bonds involve big US banks as paying agents, and if =
those banks won=E2=80=99t move the money then the money won=E2=80=99t move.=
 And then Russia will be in default on its bonds, an outcome that it would =
prefer to avoid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It =E2=80=A6=C2=A0<em>feel=
s </em>=E2=80=A6=C2=A0like there could be a workaround? Like in some loose =
sense, one wants to say =E2=80=9CRussia should simply send dollars to its b=
ondholders without involving those US banks.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But that is a co=
nceptual error. A dollar=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>an entry on the books of a U=
S bank. If you own dollars, what you own is a number in an account at a US =
bank.[1] Moving dollars means telling US=C2=A0banks to reduce the number in=
 your account and increase the number in someone else=E2=80=99s account. If=
 you cut the US banks out of the process, there=E2=80=99s no process.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there are some imperfect workarounds. One =
is: I say that a dollar=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>an entry on the books of a US=
 bank, and that is mostly true, but=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>dollars are gre=
en pieces of paper, actual physical currency. If Russia has enough of those=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I have no idea if it does =E2=80=94=C2=A0then I guess i=
t could put them in sacks and say to the bondholders =E2=80=9Chey if you wa=
nt your interest payments come to Moscow and take a sack.=E2=80=9D This is =
a very imperfect way to do international finance, and I assume a lot of int=
ernational bondholders would not want to come collect their sacks.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s another workaround. Roughly speaking=
, Russia still=C2=A0<em>has </em>its frozen US dollars. It can=E2=80=99t ma=
ke its US banks transfer them, but I suppose it could issue transferable cl=
aims on them. For instance, if Russia=E2=80=99s government holds $1 billion=
 in an account at a Russian bank, and that Russian bank in turn holds that =
$1 billion in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2789=
9761.281614/aHR0cHM6Ly9iYW0ua2FsenVtZXVzLmNvbS9hcmNoaXZlL21vdmluZy1tb25leS1=
pbnRlcm5hdGlvbmFsbHkv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a4e3957" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a US corre=
spondent bank</a>, then in some sense the $1 billion in the correspondent b=
ank=E2=80=99s accounts are =E2=80=9Creal dollars=E2=80=9D and the $1 billio=
n in the Russian bank=E2=80=99s accounts are =E2=80=9Cindirect claims on do=
llars.=E2=80=9D If Russia=E2=80=99s government called up the correspondent =
bank to say =E2=80=9Chey send that $1 billion to our bondholders,=E2=80=9D =
the correspondent bank, being US-regulated, would say no.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But if it called up the Russian bank and said =E2=80=9Chey s=
end that $1 billion to our bondholders,=E2=80=9D the Russian bank, being Ru=
ssia-regulated, would say yes. It couldn=E2=80=99t use the US banking syste=
m to do that, but it could=C2=A0<em>open accounts for the bondholders</em>=
=C2=A0at the Russian bank, and move dollars into their accounts, and then t=
he bondholders would =E2=80=9Chave=E2=80=9D the dollars. They would have nu=
mbers in their accounts at the Russian bank, and those numbers would have d=
ollar signs in front of them, and those numbers would represent claims on d=
ollars in US bank accounts even if they are not exactly interchangeable wit=
h those dollars.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the bondholders=
=C2=A0could try to withdraw the dollars, I guess, by telling the Russian ba=
nk to transfer the money to their accounts at their US banks. That is where=
 the system breaks down a bit: If you are the US bank, and you know that th=
is transfer comes from the Russian bond payment, do you reject it as a poss=
ible sanctions violation? I am not sure this actually gets usable dollars i=
nto the hands of the bondholders.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sti=
ll, Russia is going to=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/27899761.281614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjItMDUtMjkvcnVzc2lhLXRvLXNldHRsZS1ldXJvYm9uZC1kZWJ0LWluLW1pcnJvci1v=
Zi1ldS1wYXltZW50cy1mb3ItZ2FzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MzEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9b5208e8" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">try that on=
e</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia is planning a bon=
d-payment mechanism to sidestep US sanctions and a potential default as a g=
race period ticks down on its latest missed coupons.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The proposal would allow foreign investors to open accounts in Ru=
ssian banks in both rubles and hard currency, Finance Minister Anton Siluan=
ov said in an interview with the Vedomosti newspaper. Unlike the previous p=
ayment system, investors will be able to access the funds without restricti=
on, he was cited as saying. =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Russia i=
s back in default countdown as coupon payments in euros and dollars worth a=
bout $100 million had yet to trickle through to foreign investors=E2=80=99 =
accounts as of Friday evening, effectively triggering a 30-day grace period=
.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The transfers were complicated last=
 week when the US Treasury allowed a sanctions loophole to expire, barring =
US banks and individuals from accepting bond payments from Russia=E2=80=99s=
 government.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The next slate of payments -- =
worth about $400 million and due in June -- will take place =E2=80=9Coutsid=
e Western financial infrastructure,=E2=80=9D Siluanov said in an interview =
shown Monday by Chinese state-run broadcaster CGTN. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is how it works for gas payments: we get=
 foreign currency, then it is converted to rubles=E2=80=9D on behalf of the=
 gas buyer, Vedomosti cited him as saying. =E2=80=9CThe Eurobond settlement=
 mechanism will operate in the same way, but in the opposite direction.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI doubt it will w=
ork -- for most foreign investors, the procedure for opening an account wit=
h a Russian bank may be too difficult,=E2=80=9D said Alexey Tretyakov, a po=
rtfolio manager at Aricapital in Moscow.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">=E2=80=9COnly the largest institutional investors can cope. But they ma=
y face reputation risks and risks of sanctions violations when dealing with=
 Russian counterparts.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Yeah I mean having some US dollars in your bank account at a Russian bank=
 is=C2=A0<em>something</em>, though it is not quite as good as having US do=
llars in your bank account at a US bank.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-spon=
