om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Twitter Stuff</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory, the directors of a public c=
ompany are elected by the company=E2=80=99s shareholders. Each year, some o=
r all of the directors are up for re-election. If a majority of the shares =
are voted to re-elect a director, she is re-elected. If not =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=
uh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what? Every so often there are contested elections: This =
is generally called a =E2=80=9Cproxy fight=E2=80=9D; an activist investor o=
r hostile bidder or someone will nominate a slate of directors to run again=
st the incumbent directors, the activist will put a lot of time and money a=
nd effort into soliciting votes, and whoever gets the most votes for each s=
eat wins.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that happens only very occasi=
onally; almost all director elections are unopposed.=C2=A0Your choices are =
not Candidate X vs. Candidate Y; they are =E2=80=9Cfor=E2=80=9D the only ca=
ndidate=C2=A0or=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cagainst.=E2=80=9D The <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27899761.281614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubHcuY29tL=
3Rob3VnaHRMZWFkZXJzaGlwL2ltcGxlbWVudGF0aW9uLW9mLW1ham9yaXR5LXZvdGluZy1kZXRh=
aWxz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76175dc0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">traditional rule</a> of U.S=
. corporate governance was that whoever gets the most votes for each board =
seat wins, even if there is only one person running. If a candidate runs un=
opposed, and 1% of the shares are voted for her and 99% are voted against h=
er, then she has more votes than anyone else (there is no one else) and she=
 wins.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This system worked fine when everyon=
e voted for all the directors, but in recent decades it has become more com=
mon for shareholders to vote against directors, even in uncontested electio=
ns, to make some sort of symbolic point. If you are a big shareholder and y=
ou don=E2=80=99t like a company=E2=80=99s executive pay or governance pract=
ices or whatever, and you engage with the directors and they ignore you, th=
en you can vote against the directors to embarrass them. This is less drast=
ic than=C2=A0<em>running a proxy fight=C2=A0</em>and trying to=C2=A0<em>act=
ually=C2=A0</em>replace the directors, but=C2=A0running a proxy fight is ex=
pensive and difficult and very much not in the wheelhouse of most big insti=
tutional investors.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eventually people=
 sort of thought this through and realized: Well, if shareholders are so ma=
d at a director that a <em>majority</em>=C2=A0of them vote against her, and=
 nothing happens, then that is sort of embarrassing for=C2=A0<em>everyone</=
em>, including the shareholders and, like, the entire system of U.S. corpor=
ate governance. So there was a movement in the 2000s to get companies to ad=
opt =E2=80=9Cmajority voting bylaws,=E2=80=9D which basically say that if m=
ore people vote against a director than for her, then she loses and has to =
leave the board; most big U.S. companies <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/27899761.281614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2lpLm9yZy9maWxlcy9p=
c3N1ZXNfYW5kX2Fkdm9jYWN5L2JvYXJkX2FjY291bnRhYmlsaXR5L21ham9yaXR5X3ZvdGluZ19=
kaXJlY3RvcnMvQ0lJJTIwTWFqb3JpdHklMjBWb3RpbmclMjBGQVElMjAxLTQtMTcucGRm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB58917513" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">now have some form</a> of that system=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSome form,=E2=80=9D though. At m=
ost big companies, it is not like a director who loses is automatically rem=
oved from the board. (In part because,=C2=A0if a director loses an=C2=A0unc=
ontested=C2=A0election, she doesn=E2=80=99t lose=C2=A0<em>to=C2=A0</em>anyo=
ne. Who gets the board seat?) The most common system is that, if a director=
 loses an uncontested election =E2=80=94=C2=A0if more shareholders vote aga=
inst her than for her =E2=80=94=C2=A0she has to submit a resignation to the=
 rest of the board. Then the rest of the board can either (1) accept her re=
signation and appoint someone else to her seat, (2) accept her resignation =
and=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>appoint anyone else, shrinking the board, or (3)=
 reject her resignation and keep her on the board despite her losing the el=
ection. It=E2=80=99s a bit more real and embarrassing than nothing, but it =
is not quite the same as a binding vote. You can lose the vote and stay on =
the board, as long as the rest of the board wants to keep you. As the Counc=
il of Institutional Investors <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/27899761.281614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2lpLm9yZy9maWxlcy9pc3N1ZXNfYW5=
kX2Fkdm9jYWN5L2JvYXJkX2FjY291bnRhYmlsaXR5L21ham9yaXR5X3ZvdGluZ19kaXJlY3Rvcn=
MvQ0lJJTIwTWFqb3JpdHklMjBWb3RpbmclMjBGQVElMjAxLTQtMTcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cC58917513" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">puts it</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The core problem persists; uncontested director elections remain f=
unctionally symbolic. ...=C2=A0Plurality-plus and majority vote standards t=
hat permit the board to reject a resignation or immediately reappoint the r=
ejected director leave the actual decision on a board member=E2=80=99s cont=
inued service in the hands of the board. In the rare cases in which directo=
rs are rejected in uncontested votes, it is not clear that the board, which=
 tends to be put on the defensive by votes against any of its members, shou=
ld be trusted to make this decision, except for a reasonable holdover perio=
d to arrange for board change.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Twitter Inc. had its annual shareholder meeting last week. This was =
weird timing, since Twitter is also in the middle of selling itself to Elon=
 Musk; the shareholder meeting to approve=C2=A0that<em>=C2=A0</em>deal shou=
ld happen within the next few months. But the annual meeting was just for o=
ld business, including the re-election of two Twitter directors. One was re=
-elected with a huge majority, but the other, Egon Durban of Silver Lake Te=
chnology Management LLC, lost; about 257.3 million shares <a href=3D"https:=
