rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked last week</a> about the US =
Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s first =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing=E2=
=80=9D enforcement action, fining BNY Mellon Investment Adviser Inc. $1.5 m=
illion for saying that some of its funds considered=C2=A0ESG factors for al=
l of their investments, even though in fact they only considered ESG factor=
s for 75% of those investments. A small fine, because the evidence of inten=
t is not snickering chats but simply an absence of ESG reports for some com=
panies. I outlined what I think a bigger greenwashing case would look like:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An ESG fund makes its ESG choi=
ces for non-ESG reasons, and has lots of emails and chat transcripts to tha=
t effect. Somewhere on the fund=E2=80=99s servers there is an email from a =
portfolio manager to its environmental analyst saying, like, =E2=80=9CThis =
company is a hideous polluter and would never meet the ESG standards that w=
e publish and that we use to attract investors, but the stock keeps going u=
p, can we ignore our standards so I can buy it,=E2=80=9D and the analyst re=
plies =E2=80=9Csure, our bonuses are more important than ESG, I=E2=80=99ll =
just write a fake report saying it=E2=80=99s good,=E2=80=9D and the portfol=
io manager replies =E2=80=9Cgreat, hope our investors don=E2=80=99t find ou=
t about this ESG fraud we=E2=80=99re doing,=E2=80=9D and the analyst replie=
s =E2=80=9Clolololol or the SEC, see you in jail!=E2=80=9D And then the SEC=
 finds that email and prints it in a complaint and the fund settles for $10=
0 million.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27899761.281614/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMzEvZGV1dHNjaGUtYmFu=
ay1zLWR3cy11bml0LXJhaWRlZC1hbWlkLWFsbGVnYXRpb25zLW9mLWdyZWVud2FzaGluZz9jbXB=
