lid; background-color: #ccc;">in Germany</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Deutsche Bank AG and its asset management unit had their Fra=
nkfurt offices raided by police, adding to the legal headaches facing Germa=
ny=E2=80=99s largest lender.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Law enforcemen=
t officials on Tuesday morning entered the twin towers where Germany=E2=80=
=99s largest lender is headquartered, as well as the nearby premises of DWS=
 Group, according to a statement from the prosecutor that confirmed an earl=
ier Bloomberg report. The search is related to accusations of greenwashing =
against the asset manager. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">DWS ha=
s faced regulatory probes in the US and Germany after its former chief sust=
ainability officer, Desiree Fixler, went public with greenwashing allegatio=
ns last year. While the company has denied the claims, the raid adds to a l=
ist of regulatory and legal issues for Deutsche Bank Chief Executive Office=
r Christian Sewing just as he emerges from a successful turnaround of the l=
ender. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among other things, Fixler=
 has said that DWS=E2=80=99s claims that hundreds of billions of its assets=
 under management were =E2=80=9CESG integrated=E2=80=9D were misleading bec=
ause the label didn=E2=80=99t translate into meaningful action by relevant =
fund managers. DWS has since stopped using the label.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See, you simply cannot storm into a bank and look f=
or evidence that the =E2=80=9CESG integrated=E2=80=9D label =E2=80=9Cdidn=
=E2=80=99t translate into meaningful action by relevant fund managers.=E2=
=80=9D That label means that the fund managers thought about ESG stuff, and=
 they thought about other stuff (will the stocks go up), and then they made=
 some decision about which stocks to buy based on some weighting=C2=A0of th=
ose factors. Buying some coal stock, or whatever, is not proof that the ESG=
-integrated fund was somehow a fraud; perhaps the managers thought really h=
ard about it and bought the stock anyway.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">W=
hat=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>arguably proof of fraud, and what you=C2=A0<em>ca=
n=C2=A0</em>find in a raid, is an email from one fund manager to another sa=
ying =E2=80=9Cthis ESG stuff is so fake, I am not really going to consider =
it in making investment decisions.=E2=80=9D Or you could find an email from=
 a sustainability analyst to the manager of an ESG-integrated fund saying =
=E2=80=9Cthis company is the worst polluter in Europe, you should not buy i=
ts stock for your fund,=E2=80=9D and the manager replying =E2=80=9Cbuzz off=
, sustainability nerd, I=E2=80=99ll buy whatever I want, ESG is fake.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, there is a danger here. The=
 more passionate ESG analysts you hire, the more likely they are to send pa=
ssionate emails saying =E2=80=9Cwe can=E2=80=99t buy this stock, it=E2=80=
=99s a terrible polluter.=E2=80=9D Sometimes they will be right and you won=
=E2=80=99t buy the stock. Other times, the ESG-integrated fund managers wil=
l consider their input carefully and then say =E2=80=9CI see your point, bu=
t I think you are overstating the problem, and anyway our mandate is to con=
sider other factors, so I am going to buy some of the stock despite your ob=
jections.=E2=80=9D And then the passionate analyst will reply =E2=80=9Cyou =
monster, you are destroying the planet.=E2=80=9D And then the regulators wi=
ll find those emails and you will get in trouble for greenwashing.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are about three ways to avoid this:</p><ol st=
yle=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Do everything that your most passionate ESG=
 analysts advocate, to avoid getting in trouble for contradicting them.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Have a rigorous culture of not puttin=
g anything in writing, to avoid creating any embarrassing records.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Don=E2=80=99t hire particularly passionate=
 ESG analysts.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The more that your cul=
ture encourages passionate analysts to advocate for tough ESG policies,=C2=
=A0<em>the more awkward emails you will generate</em>.[2] If you treat ESG =
as a box-ticking exercise, the raids will find nothing. If you have robust =
internal debates about ESG, some of those debates will leak out, the raids =
will find the most passionate objections that were overruled and they will =
look pretty bad. And because greenwashing is doing bad ESG stuff <em>and se=
nding emails about it</em>, you will get in trouble.</p><table class=3D"hea=
